Absolutely. Here’s a repo-ready design for it.

Presence-Gated Privacy Window

Working name: privacy-window
Core idea: Sensitive UI is rendered only while the enrolled user’s face is actively present, live, and attending. Unlock is not enough. Visibility is continuously gated.

⸻

1. Product thesis

Traditional mobile auth answers:

“Who unlocked the device?”

This system answers:

“Who is perceiving the content right now?”

That shifts security from a one-time gate to a continuous disclosure control layer.

⸻

2. Primary use case

A phone may already be unlocked, but certain content should still remain hidden unless the owner’s face is actively in frame.

Examples:
	•	hidden notes
	•	private albums
	•	balances / wallet contents
	•	selected chats
	•	vault files
	•	admin settings
	•	recovery keys
	•	sensitive autofill data
	•	“second layer” content inside normal apps

⸻

3. Threat model

Defends against
	•	casual snooping on an already-unlocked phone
	•	partner/friend/coworker grabbing the device
	•	brief handoff situations
	•	shoulder surfing
	•	inattentive exposure when owner looks away
	•	accidental reveals while screen is shared nearby

Partially defends against
	•	someone holding the phone near your face
	•	someone reading over your shoulder while your face is present
	•	replay attempts with photos/videos unless liveness is strong

Does not defend against
	•	coercion
	•	system compromise / malware with deep privileges
	•	external camera filming the screen while content is visible
	•	screenshots if OS integration is weak
	•	mirrored display leakage unless blocked at compositor layer

⸻

4. Product modes

Mode A — App Lock+

Certain apps only reveal content when presence verification passes.

Examples:
	•	vault app
	•	notes tagged private
	•	hidden album
	•	password manager

Mode B — Field-Level Privacy

Normal app opens, but certain fields remain masked unless the face gate is active.

Examples:
	•	message preview text
	•	account balances
	•	contact names
	•	document sections
	•	secret tabs

Mode C — Dual Semantic Layer

The app always shows something, but the meaning changes based on viewer presence.

Examples:
	•	decoy notes vs real notes
	•	normal photo library vs hidden album
	•	bland finance dashboard vs detailed holdings
	•	public thread titles vs actual private messages

Mode D — Panic Fade

When your face disappears or an unknown face appears, the UI immediately:
	•	blurs
	•	masks
	•	swaps to decoy
	•	jumps to innocuous screen
	•	locks sensitive pane only

⸻

5. System architecture

Front Camera / Sensor Layer
        ↓
Identity & Liveness Engine
        ↓
Presence Confidence Engine
        ↓
Policy Engine
        ↓
Secure Render Controller
        ↓
App / Field / Overlay Visibility


⸻

6. Core modules

6.1 Sensor layer

Inputs:
	•	front-facing camera
	•	depth / IR camera if available
	•	gaze / attention signals if available
	•	ambient light
	•	motion / IMU context
	•	proximity sensor

Purpose:
	•	determine whether a face is present
	•	determine whether that face matches enrolled identity
	•	determine whether it is live
	•	determine whether attention is directed toward screen

⸻

6.2 Identity engine

Responsibilities:
	•	face embedding extraction
	•	face match against enrolled template
	•	multi-frame stabilization
	•	anti-spoof / liveness checks
	•	confidence scoring

Outputs:

{
  "face_present": true,
  "identity_match": 0.94,
  "liveness_score": 0.91,
  "attention_score": 0.77,
  "num_faces": 1,
  "occlusion_score": 0.12
}


⸻

6.3 Presence confidence engine

Takes noisy frame-by-frame data and turns it into stable control signals.

This is critical. You do not want UI flickering every time the face shifts.

Suggested derived score

presence_confidence =
  w1 * identity_match +
  w2 * liveness_score +
  w3 * attention_score +
  w4 * continuity_bonus -
  w5 * occlusion_penalty -
  w6 * multi_face_penalty

Use:
	•	exponential moving average
	•	hysteresis thresholds
	•	grace timers
	•	fast hide / slow reveal

Example thresholds
	•	reveal if confidence > 0.87 for 400 ms
	•	maintain visible until confidence < 0.68 for 700 ms
	•	immediate hide if unknown second face detected for 150 ms
	•	immediate hide if camera feed fails in high-security mode

⸻

6.4 Policy engine

This is the heart of the product.

A policy decides what content needs what level of presence proof.

Example policy object

{
  "resource_id": "notes/private/*",
  "mode": "face_required",
  "min_identity_match": 0.90,
  "min_liveness": 0.80,
  "min_attention": 0.60,
  "hide_delay_ms": 300,
  "reveal_delay_ms": 450,
  "multi_face_action": "hide",
  "failure_action": "blur",
  "screenshot_block": true,
  "screen_record_block": true
}

Policy classes
	•	public
	•	masked_until_presence
	•	presence_required
	•	presence_and_attention_required
	•	presence_with_decoy_fallback
	•	presence_with_panic_lock

⸻

6.5 Secure render controller

Do not just let apps draw the secret content normally and blur it afterward.

That leaks.

Instead use a secure rendering path where:
	•	protected regions are separate layers
	•	hidden state means pixels are never composed
	•	screenshots exclude protected layers
	•	screen recording excludes protected layers
	•	app switcher thumbnails redact protected layers
	•	external display / AirPlay / casting suppresses protected layers

This is one of the most important design choices.

⸻

7. UX behavior

7.1 Normal flow
	1.	user unlocks phone
	2.	opens an app
	3.	app shows safe/default shell
	4.	presence engine confirms enrolled user is present
	5.	private content fades in
	6.	user looks away or leaves frame
	7.	private content blurs or disappears
	8.	return to shell state

7.2 Visual states

Each protected component has four states:
	•	hidden
	•	arming
	•	visible
	•	decoy

Example

A chat thread:
	•	hidden: “Private conversation”
	•	arming: spinning privacy glyph
	•	visible: real thread text
	•	decoy: generic old messages or empty thread shell

⸻

8. Recommended UX principles

Make hide faster than reveal

Reveal should require confidence.
Hide should be aggressive.

Never flicker

Use hysteresis and smoothing.

Local-first

Face processing should stay on device.

Give user control

Per-app and per-folder rules.

Always provide a benign fallback

Don’t leave awkward black voids everywhere unless user wants that.

⸻

9. Detection logic

Inputs evaluated continuously
	•	is an enrolled face present?
	•	is it live?
	•	is user oriented toward screen?
	•	is there more than one face?
	•	did the face just disappear?
	•	did an unrecognized face enter?
	•	is phone being shared / mirrored?
	•	is screen recording active?
	•	is app backgrounded?

Event triggers

ON_AUTHORIZED_FACE_STABLE
ON_AUTHORIZED_FACE_LOST
ON_UNKNOWN_FACE_DETECTED
ON_MULTI_FACE_DETECTED
ON_ATTENTION_LOST
ON_SCREEN_RECORD_START
ON_APP_BACKGROUND
ON_CAMERA_UNAVAILABLE


⸻

10. State machine

LOCKED
  ↓ unlock
SAFE_VISIBLE
  ↓ authorized face stable
PRIVATE_ARMING
  ↓ confidence sustained
PRIVATE_VISIBLE
  ↓ confidence drop
PRIVATE_HOLD
  ↓ recovers quickly → PRIVATE_VISIBLE
  ↓ timeout / intrusion → PRIVATE_HIDDEN
PRIVATE_HIDDEN
  ↓ stable reauth → PRIVATE_ARMING
DECOY_MODE
  ↓ user reauth → PRIVATE_ARMING


⸻

11. Security policies by sensitivity

Tier 0 — Public

No gating.

Tier 1 — Soft private

Requires face presence.
Failure action: blur.

Tier 2 — Strong private

Requires face + liveness.
Failure action: remove content.

Tier 3 — Critical

Requires face + liveness + attention.
Failure action: lock pane, redact app switcher, block screenshots, block screen recording, hide on multi-face.

⸻

12. Attack scenarios and responses

Scenario: phone unlocked, wrong person picks it up

Response:
	•	protected layers never reveal
	•	safe shell only

Scenario: owner hands phone to someone to show one photo

Response:
	•	gallery visible
	•	hidden album stays absent unless owner’s face present

Scenario: second face appears beside owner

Response options:
	•	immediately blur
	•	darken protected pane
	•	require attention re-check
	•	swap to public-only mode

Scenario: owner briefly looks away

Response:
	•	short hold buffer, maybe 300–700 ms
	•	if attention absent persists, mask content

Scenario: spoof with printed photo

Response:
	•	liveness gate
	•	depth / IR / micro-motion checks
	•	challenge on high-risk access if needed

⸻

13. Privacy posture

This product can become creepy if done wrong.

So the design should explicitly include:
	•	on-device processing only
	•	no face video upload
	•	no identity analytics beyond local match
	•	no persistent recording
	•	ephemeral face frames only
	•	user-visible sensor indicator
	•	clear explanation of what is and isn’t stored

Suggested invariant

The camera is used to gate visibility, not to surveil behavior.

